Gaul was divided by the Romans into Gallia Transalpina, or Ulterior, Farther Gaul,- or Gaul beyond the Alps; and Gallia Cisalpina, or Cite- rior, Hither Gaul, or Gaul on this side of the Alps, in regard to Rome. Hither Gaul was also called Gallia Togata, because the inhabitants were admitted to the privilege of Roman citizens, aud wore the toga, the peculial· dress of the Romans. Farther Gaul was called Comata, from the natives wearing their hair long 3 and the southern part of it Bmccata, from the use of braccoe, breeches or trousers, which did not form a part of the Roman dress. Gaul was called by the Greeks Galatia, and the inhabi- tants Galatae.
